INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3000','letter','1776-08-28','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','As the smallpox is now perfectly removed from the army, I shall, in consequence of the intelligence received of the motions of the enemy, immediately assemble my principal strength to maintain this important pass','ltr_hog3000.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3001','letter','1777-08-22','','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','Upon my leaving Philadelphia, the prospect this way appeared most gloomy, but the severe checks the enemy have met with at Bennington and Tryon county, have given a more pleasing view of public affairs.','ltr_hog3001.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3002','letter','1777-10-05','Behmus Heights','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am sorry to repeat to your Excellency the Distress I have suffered for want of a proper supply of musket cartridges from Springfield, or the materials to make them.','ltr_hog3002.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3003','letter','1776-08-07','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','Benedict','Arnold','','individual','','You will station the fleet in the best manner to maintain the possession of those passes, according as your judgment shall determine, cautiously avoiding to place the vessels in a manner, which might unnecessarily expose them','ltr_hog3003.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3004','letter','1776-10-31','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','Philip','Schuyler','','individual','','Monday morning, between eight and nine o clock, our advanced guard-boat, down the Lake, made the signal for the approach of the enemy\'s fleet. In about one hour, five of their largest boats or gondolas appeared in sight','ltr_hog3004.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3005','letter','1776-11-05','Ticonderoga','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','','','','position','The President Of Congress','I have the honor to congratulate Congress upon the retreat of Lieutenant-General Sir Guy Carleton, with the fleet and army under his command, from Crown Point, Saturday last.','ltr_hog3005.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3200','letter','1777-11-23','Albany','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have never entertained the smallest idea that General Burgoyne should be permitted to ex change the port of embarkation, or that the least variation of the spirit and letter of the Convention would be indulged to the troops under his command.','ltr_hog3200.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3201','letter','1778-06-25','Peekskill','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','To prevent the enemy\'s army, now marching across the Jerseys, from receiving any considerable reenforcement from the troops in and near New York, I propose moving the main body of this army to the White Plains','ltr_hog3201.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3202','letter','1778-09-30','Danbury','STATE','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am sorry for the disgrace we have suffered in the Jerseys; but imagine that the enemy take ad vantage of the supine ness that constantly seizes our people, when they have been long unmolested.','ltr_hog3202.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3203','letter','1779-03-04','Boston','MA','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am sorry to find your Excellency seems to have given over all thoughts of penetrating into Canada by the route of Coos','ltr_hog3203.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3204','letter','1779-11-08','Providence','RI','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','Thursday night I had the honor to receive your Excellency\'s letter of the 1st instant, and immediately gave orders for moving the Continental troops over the bay to Greenwich','ltr_hog3204.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3205','letter','1779-11-15','Hartford','CT','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Washington','','individual','','In obedience to the orders contained in your Excellency\'s letters of the 1st and 2d instant, I marched the whole of the Continental troops from the State of Rhode Island, and arrived yesterday morning','ltr_hog3205.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3206','letter','1777-09-02','City','STATE','US','Horatio','Gates','','Simon','Fraser','','individual','','Surgeons, medicines, and attendance, with every comfort imaginable, have been amply supplied to the sick and wounded officers and soldiers, prisoners at Bennington','ltr_hog3206.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3207','letter','1777-09-19','Behmus Heights','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','Benjamin','Lincoln','','individual','','in the present position and circumstances of General Burgoyne\'s army, considered with his apparent views, your army ought to be posted at Stillwater','ltr_hog3207.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3208','letter','1777-11-02','Albany','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','Israel','Putnam','','individual','','As to any attack upon New York, I utterly disapprove of it; for, while the enemy\'s ships of war can act in the North and East Rivers, the taking of that city would be doubtful','ltr_hog3208.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3209','letter','1778-03-02','York','','US','Horatio','Gates','','John','Burgoyne','','individual','','I am exceedingly mortified that you did not accept of my offer at Albany, to go to England in a vessel, that the State of Massachusetts Bay would, at my request, have provided.','ltr_hog3209.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3210','letter','1777-10-29','Albany','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Clinton','','individual','','As I have not heard a syllable from you, or General Putnam, for a week past, I conclude you are in no want of any further assistance from me.','ltr_hog3210.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_hog3211','letter','1777-11-02','Albany','NY','US','Horatio','Gates','','George','Clinton','','individual','','If Sir Henry Clinton marches towards Mount Holly, our army will, of course, move directly to Princeton, and hang upon his rear and right flank. If he marches towards Trenton, our army will march to Somerset','ltr_hog3211.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
